      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

I think that the simplest explanation might be that Elon Musk does not know=
 what a merger agreement is. It is not uncommon, in the world, for two comp=
anies to get together and discuss one buying the other. And sometimes these=
 talks will go well and they will get together and=C2=A0sign some sort of d=
ocument =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cmemorandum of understanding,=E2=80=9D per=
haps =E2=80=94=C2=A0that says, basically, =E2=80=9Cnow we are going to talk=
 really seriously about me buying you.=E2=80=9D Sometimes they will have a =
price lined up=C2=A0when they sign this document, say $54.20,=C2=A0and=C2=
=A0that price will be written into the document, and the expectation will b=
e that eventually the buyer will pay $54.20 to buy the seller. But things c=
an go wrong. There will be continuing due diligence, where the buyer examin=
es the seller=E2=80=99s business, and the buyer might change its mind. Fact=
s might come to light in due diligence that could make the buyer walk away =
or want to revise the price downward. The market might crash, making the se=
ller less valuable or making it harder for the buyer to get financing.=C2=
=A0The MOU is an agreement to talk more seriously; it reflects a general mu=
tual desire to come to a deal at $54.20, but it is not binding. Nobody is c=
ommitted to a deal at $54.20. Nothing is certain until the final deal is si=
gned.
That, again, is a description of=C2=A0a thing that can happen in the world;=
 some business acquisitions do go through a process=C2=A0like that. But it =
is not a description of US public-company merger agreements. In normal US p=
ublic-company mergers, you don=E2=80=99t sign a memorandum saying =E2=80=9C=
we=E2=80=99re going to negotiate seriously about buying you.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0You=C2=A0negotiate seriously, and then=C2=A0you sign a merger agreeme=
nt saying =E2=80=9Cwe agree to buy you for $54.20.=E2=80=9D And then if the=
 buyer changes its mind, it still has to pay $54.20. And if the market cras=
hes, the buyer still has to pay $54.20. The deal is the deal; once it is si=
gned, the merger agreement is binding and definitive.
  [2]

It is confusing, though. When you sign a public-company merger agreement, y=
ou do not immediately own the company you are buying. You are still months,=
 perhaps years, away from the =E2=80=9Cclosing=E2=80=9D of the deal, when y=
ou actually pay the money and=C2=A0take over the company. The delay is nece=
ssary to get regulatory approvals (antitrust, etc.), and to write a proxy s=
tatement and submit the merger to a vote of the target=E2=80=99s shareholde=
rs. (You sign the merger agreement with the target=E2=80=99s board of direc=
tors, but they don=E2=80=99t get the final say; the shareholders do.) Also,=
 if you need to borrow money to buy the target, this delay gives you time t=
o market the debt and actually get the money. (When you sign the deal, you =
probably=C2=A0have commitment letters from your banks promising you the mon=
ey, but by closing you can actually have the specific loans in place.)
And during this delay, things can go wrong. The regulators might not approv=
e. The shareholders might vote no. The financing might fall apart.
  [3]
=C2=A0When you sign the merger agreement, the buyer and seller agree to wor=
k together and use their =E2=80=9Creasonable best efforts=E2=80=9D to get t=
he regulatory approvals and shareholder vote and financing and everything e=
lse needed for the deal to close, but even if they do all of that sometimes=
 it=E2=80=99s not enough, and the deal falls apart. Signing a merger agreem=
ent doesn=E2=80=99t mean that the buyer will=C2=A0definitely=C2=A0buy the s=
eller. It is a serious binding commitment, but it is not 100%.
If you are the buyer, you might think about=C2=A0other=C2=A0things that mig=
ht go wrong. What if the seller=E2=80=99s business all burns to the ground =
in a fire? Seems unfair for you to have to buy it anyway. What if the fire =
was the seller=E2=80=99s fault? What if it turns out that the seller was ru=
nning a massive fraud and the whole business is fake? Seems really unfair f=
or you to have to buy it anyway.
And so, yes, even if you get the regulatory and shareholder approvals and t=
he financing, there are still times when a buyer can get out of a deal betw=
een signing and closing. But they are quite limited. The main one is that t=
he seller makes representations in the merger agreement =E2=80=94=C2=A0stat=
ements about the company that it promises are true, things like =E2=80=9Cou=
r financial statements are true=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe are not breaking a=
ny laws=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and if those statements are false, and=
 they are=C2=A0so=C2=A0false that they would have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adver=
se effect=E2=80=9D on the business, then the buyer can get out of the deal.=
 (A typo in the financial statements is not enough to get out of the deal, =
but inflating revenue for years might be.) That is a high bar, and=C2=A0Del=
aware courts =E2=80=94=C2=A0which hear most big merger cases, since most pu=
blic companies are incorporated in Delaware =E2=80=94   almost never find M=
AEs. But in theory, yes, if the buyer was misled and the seller=E2=80=99s b=
usiness is falling apart, the buyer can get out. And there are a very few o=
ther possible excuses; for instance, if the seller does not comply with its=
 covenants =E2=80=94=C2=A0the things that it agreed to do between signing a=
nd closing =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the buyer   might have an out. Or if the buy=
er was tricked into signing the merger agreement by   intentional and mater=
ial=C2=A0fraud, that would be an out.
But the buyer can=E2=80=99t get out because it changed its mind. Or because=
 the market went down and it is overpaying. Or because the market went down=
 and it doesn=E2=80=99t have as much money as it used to. Or because the se=
ller=E2=80=99s business turns out to be worse than the buyer thought in a g=
eneral way. Broadly speaking, the merger agreement is meant to be binding. =
Getting out of it is the exception.
Elon Musk is trying to get out of the merger agreement he signed in April=
=C2=A0to buy Twitter Inc. for $54.20 per share, or about $44 billion total.=
 He has good professional lawyers, and they are working hard, and certainly=
=C2=A0they know what a merger agreement is, so all of Musk=E2=80=99s offici=
al statements and legal filings and so forth are phrased in terms of covena=
nt violations and material adverse effects and fraud.
But it seems completely obvious to me that=C2=A0Musk doesn=E2=80=99t care a=
bout those magic words, and that he wants to get out of the deal for some c=
ombination of (1) the market went down and $54.20 per share=C2=A0looks pret=
ty rich for Twitter, (2) the market went down and $44 billion looks like a =
big hit to Musk=E2=80=99s own wealth, and (3) he wanted to buy Twitter on a=
 whim and he=E2=80=99s gotten bored by now. I have been saying this for mon=
ths and I am bored of it and I=E2=80=99m sure you are too, so I am not goin=
g to rehash the point here.
  [4]

Instead I will just point out that Musk=E2=80=99s own=C2=A0statements =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0not the ones from his lawyers in court =E2=80=94=C2=A0suggest t=
hat he doesn=E2=80=99t know what a merger agreement is. The first sign that=
 he wanted out of the deal was back in May, barely two weeks after he signe=
d the deal,  when he tweeted =E2=80=9CTwitter deal temporarily on hold pend=
ing details supporting calculation that spam/fake accounts do indeed repres=
ent less than 5% of users.=E2=80=9D No! No! No!=C2=A0As   I said at the tim=
e:
=E2=80=9CTemporarily on hold=E2=80=9D is not a thing. Elon Musk has signed =
a binding contract requiring him to buy Twitter. Legions of bankers and law=
yers and Twitter employees and special-purpose-vehicle promoters are workin=
g to fulfill his legal obligation to get the deal closed. =E2=80=9CThe part=
ies hereto will use their respective reasonable best efforts to consummate =
and make effective the transactions contemplated by this Agreement,=E2=80=
=9D says the merger agreement. (Section 6.3(a).) He can=E2=80=99t just put =
that =E2=80=9Con hold.=E2=80=9D
If you were in the process of=C2=A0negotiating a merger, and then you got n=
ervous that some element of the company=E2=80=99s business might not be wha=
t you thought, you might put the negotiations =E2=80=9Con hold.=E2=80=9D Yo=
u might demand more information about the company=E2=80=99s bot calculation=
s, and you might stop negotiating other details of the deal until you got i=
t. If the information wasn=E2=80=99t what you wanted, you might walk away, =
or demand a lower price. All of these things are things that could happen b=
efore you sign a merger agreement. Not, generally, after.
Yesterday there was a big hearing in Delaware Chancery Court on the Musk/Tw=
itter lawsuit. Some of it was about discovery issues =E2=80=94=C2=A0Musk an=
d Twitter have been demanding information from each other, and fighting abo=
ut what they have to provide and when. But the more important part was abou=
t whether Musk can amend his claims to add more reasons to get out of the d=
eal. Initially, Musk argued that he could get out of his deal to buy Twitte=
r mostly for reasons relating to his apparent belief that Twitter has too m=
any bots. But then last month Twitter=E2=80=99s former head of security, Pe=
iter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko, publicized a whistle-blower complaint a=
rguing that Twitter does a bunch of other bad things, and Musk wants to add=
 those claims to his arguments. If Twitter has bad information security pra=
ctices, then maybe that=E2=80=99s fraud, or maybe its representations are f=
alse and there=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a material adverse effect, and Musk might as =
well argue that too.
At the hearing, Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers argued that Zatko=E2=80=99s claims=
=C2=A0might be true, and if they are then they might give Musk a way out of=
 the deal, and so we=C2=A0might as well find out. And Twitter=E2=80=99s law=
yers argued that Musk is just fishing for excuses to get out of the deal.=
=C2=A0(Disclosure, Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers are at Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen=
 & Katz, where I used to work.) As Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Kurt Wagner and Je=
f Feeley=C2=A0report:

Bill Savitt, an attorney for Twitter, brought up a text message between Mus=
k and one of his bankers as evidence during a Chancery Court hearing Tuesda=
y. In the message from May 8, Musk asked the banker to slow down the deal p=
rocess until after Russian President Vladimir Putin gave a speech the follo=
wing day, during which Putin defended his decision to invade Ukraine.
=E2=80=9CIt won=E2=80=99t make sense to buy Twitter if we=E2=80=99re headin=
g into World War III,=E2=80=9D Musk wrote. He had already agreed to buy Twi=
tter for $44 billion two weeks earlier.

Yes, right, see, if the global environment has gotten worse for business, i=
t is perfectly reasonable for a rich businessman to text the bankers who ar=
e negotiating a merger=C2=A0to  tell them =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s slow down =
just a few days.=E2=80=9D You don=E2=80=99t want to sign a merger agreement=
 if things are getting worse! At least you=E2=80=99ll want to rethink the p=
rice.
The problem is that Musk had already signed the merger agreement. There is =
no =E2=80=9Con hold,=E2=80=9D no =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s slow down,=E2=80=9D=
 once you sign. You have committed to use your reasonable best efforts to g=
et the deal done, and when you text your bankers to tell them to maybe use =
their third-best efforts to get it done, you are breaching the agreement.
Or:
A lawyer for Twitter also disclosed during the hearing about a discussion b=
etween/with Musk and third party banker Perella Weinberg in mid June about =
using a contingent value right, or CVR, as a way to renegotiate the Twitter=
 (TWTR) deal.
A  CVR is a way to bridge a valuation gap in a merger negotiation. If a pot=
ential buyer thinks that a company is worth $45, and a seller won=E2=80=99t=
 take less than $54.20, perhaps you can use a CVR to get a deal done. =E2=
=80=9CI will pay you $45,=E2=80=9D the buyer says, =E2=80=9Cbut I will pay =
you another $9.20 if the business hits certain revenue milestones in the ye=
ar after I buy it.=E2=80=9D And then if the business is as good as the sell=
ers think it is they get their $54.20, but if it isn=E2=80=99t then the buy=
er only pays $45.
But the Twitter situation is the opposite of that. Twitter=E2=80=99s shareh=
olders thought it was worth about $45, tops, and then Musk   came along out=
 of nowhere and   bid $54.20 for it, and Twitter=E2=80=99s   board was like=
 =E2=80=9Csure if you want to pay us $54.20 we=E2=80=99ll take it.=E2=80=9D=
 And then they signed a deal at a fixed price. And then Musk decided a few =
weeks later that that price was a bit rich, so he considered proposing=C2=
=A0a CVR. To bridge the gap between the price he agreed to pay and the pric=
e he=E2=80=99d rather pay. Again, it doesn=E2=80=99t work that way.=C2=A0
Or Savitt at one point in the hearing=C2=A0 said: =E2=80=9CYou don't do due=
 diligence to get out of a merger agreement, you do it to get into one.=E2=
=80=9D Musk signed a merger agreement, and then started to do due diligence=
, at which point he got nervous about the bots.=C2=A0Savitt is right: You d=
o the diligence=C2=A0before=C2=A0you sign the merger agreement. But if you =
don=E2=80=99t know how merger agreements work, you might get this reversed.
I think this stuff is just obviously true. I think it is clear that Elon Mu=
sk doesn=E2=80=99t believe in binding merger agreements, and he changed his=
 mind about buying Twitter and now wants his merger agreement to go away. A=
nd everything else =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stuff about bots, the stuff about the=
 whistle-blower, allegations of covenant breaches and material adverse effe=
cts and fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0is just lawyers trying to justify that.=C2=A0
But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean he=C2=A0loses. If he changed his mind about T=
witter because the market crashed,=C2=A0and also=C2=A0it turns out that Twi=
tter breached its covenants or suffered a material adverse effect or was do=
ing a massive fraud, then he (probably) gets to get out of the deal. That w=
ould be kind of a weird coincidence, but honestly not=C2=A0that=C2=A0weird.=
 Most of the time when a merger is terminated   or renegotiated,=C2=A0it is=
 for some combination of (1) the buyer got market-driven cold feet and (2) =
it found something bad about the target that gave it an excuse. And=C2=A0Tw=
itter is an odd=C2=A0and broken company,=C2=A0which is explicitly  why Musk=
 wanted to buy it, so it wouldn=E2=80=99t be hugely surprising if it was br=
oken in particular ways that breached a standard merger agreement. Even if =
Musk is just looking for excuses to get out of the deal, that doesn=E2=80=
=99t mean he can=E2=80=99t find one.=C2=A0
Musk=E2=80=99s main requests at yesterday=E2=80=99s hearing were:
=09To amend his counterclaims to put in all of Zatko=E2=80=99s claims about=
 fraud.=09To get to do more discovery, demanding more documents from Twitte=
r about Zatko=E2=80=99s claims.=09To delay the trial, currently scheduled f=
or October, so he could have more time to do all of this.

This morning the judge, Chancellor Kathaleen McCormick, ruled on his reques=
ts, and I think  her opinion is a fairly clear win for Twitter. She will le=
t Musk amend his claims, which is technically a win for him, but which to s=
ome extent limits his freedom of action. If she had said no, he could have =
appealed. (He would have had a good argument; the standard for amending cla=
ims is low.)=C2=A0He could have found another court to sue in, some other a=
udience to listen to him. But now he has to argue about Zatko=E2=80=99s com=
plaint in Chancellor McCormick=E2=80=99s court, alongside all of his other =
excuses for getting out of the deal. She has the relevant context.=C2=A0
She will also let Musk do a little bit of discovery on those claims, but no=
t too much. (=E2=80=9CDefendants are permitted only incremental discovery r=
elevant to the new allegations. That discovery can be made through targeted=
 document discovery and minimal additional experts and fact witnesses.=E2=
=80=9D)
And, crucially, she won=E2=80=99t push back the trial, which is still sched=
uled to start on Oct. 17. If you looked at this case and thought =E2=80=9Cu=
h oh, Twitter has been running a massive fraud and Elon Musk just learned a=
bout it,=E2=80=9D you would want to push back the trial to let him find out=
 more about the fraud. If you looked at it and thought =E2=80=9Cwow, Elon M=
usk keeps coming up with new excuses to get out of the merger agreement he =
signed, and here=E2=80=99s another one,=E2=80=9D you would let him=C2=A0arg=
ue=C2=A0about that excuse, but you wouldn=E2=80=99t give him any more time.=
 You would want to make sure that you=E2=80=99ve heard all of his arguments=
 before rejecting them, but you wouldn=E2=80=99t let him drag the case out =
forever.=C2=A0
It is relevant here, I think, that Chancellor McCormick definitely knows ho=
w merger agreements work. She is a Delaware chancellor. They do all the pub=
lic-company M&A litigation. She has   seen buyers who want to get out of me=
rgers before, and she has seen Musk=E2=80=99s claims so far. =E2=80=9CI am =
reticent to say more concerning the merits of the counterclaims at this pos=
ture before they have been fully litigated,=E2=80=9D she wrote in today=E2=
=80=99s opinion.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe world will have to wait for the post-tri=
al decision.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

