      Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20

If you are the chief executive officer of a big integrated oil company, and=
 holders of 60% of shares tell you that you should focus more on renewable =
energy, should you do it? I actually think that this is a non-obvious quest=
ion. Some considerations:
=09Possibly pivoting to renewables will cost you more money now but increas=
e long-term profits. Or perhaps not. You=E2=80=99re an oil-company CEO, tho=
ugh; I guess you=E2=80=99re the expert on allocating capital to energy proj=
ects.=C2=A0=09You are a fiduciary for shareholders and you have your own in=
dependent fiduciary obligation to do what is right for them. If you think t=
hat focusing on renewables is the best long-term value-enhancing strategy f=
or the company and its shareholders, you should do that. If you think that =
drilling more oil is the best strategy, then you are in charge, and you sho=
uld do that. Your job is not to just do whatever they say; your job is to m=
anage the company.=09That said, the shareholders are not dummies =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0certainly=C2=A0lots=C2=A0of your shares are held by institutional inv=
estors=C2=A0who are economically motivated and smart =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so =
if they think that renewables are a better strategy, you should at least he=
ar them out. It is not=C2=A0certain=C2=A0that you are a better allocator of=
 capital to energy projects than they are.=09Also, to the extent that=C2=A0=
your job is to do what is right for shareholders, their subjective preferen=
ces might factor into it.=C2=A0Like if you think that focusing more on rene=
wables will produce less income but=C2=A0make your shareholders happy, then=
, as a fiduciary for your shareholders, shouldn=E2=80=99t you do what makes=
 them happy?=09Also, to the extent that your job is to=C2=A0make the stock =
price go up=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the simplest proxy for creating shareholder=
 value =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, again, their subjective preferences might facto=
r into it. If you focus on renewables and that makes shareholders happy and=
 they buy more stock and the stock goes up, then that is what matters, not =
the income statement.=09You are a modern CEO and  you think about all stake=
holders, not just shareholder value. So even if your shareholders think you=
 should pivot to renewables and are correct that that is the right financia=
l choice, you might say =E2=80=9Cno I don=E2=80=99t want to lay off any oil=
 drillers, so I=E2=80=99m sticking with drilling.=E2=80=9D (Or: You say =E2=
=80=9Csure, shareholders, you are worried about financial returns, but I am=
 worried about Europe=E2=80=99s resolve in resisting Russian aggression, so=
 I am going to drill to keep oil prices low.=E2=80=9D Lots of stakeholders!=
)=09There is the fact that the shareholders own 60% of the stock and so the=
y get to vote on stuff, so even if you don=E2=80=99t want to do what they w=
ant, you have to consider that your job is on the line. Oh, maybe not, mayb=
e not; it is very hard for even 60% of shareholders to make=C2=A0binding=C2=
=A0changes at a big public company. But there is precedent: Exxon Mobil Cor=
p.   lost a proxy fight with a teeny tiny activist shareholder over issues =
like this. Big shareholders wanted more renewables, Exxon wasn=E2=80=99t gi=
ving them what they wanted, so the activist =E2=80=94=C2=A0a hedge fund cal=
led Engine No. 1 =E2=80=94=C2=A0ran a proxy fight and got several Exxon dir=
ectors replaced. If you ignore your shareholders=E2=80=99 demands, they mig=
ht get together and replace you too.

All in all I think the basic answer is =E2=80=9Clisten respectfully to your=
 shareholders, consider their arguments seriously, be open to changing your=
 mind, say soothing things to them, but ultimately do what you think is bes=
t for the long-term value of the company even if it=E2=80=99s not what shar=
eholders say they want, and if you get fired=C2=A0then that=E2=80=99s life.=
=E2=80=9D But I could see arguments for other approaches.
Here is an approach that I honestly had not thought of:
=09Your shareholders are not your shareholders. Most of your shares are hel=
d by big institutions like BlackRock Inc., which manage money on behalf of =
thousands of individual customers. The stated desires and subjective prefer=
ences of the managers at BlackRock Inc. are irrelevant and you should ignor=
e them. You cannot know the preferences of BlackRock=E2=80=99s=C2=A0custome=
rs, because you do not deal with them directly. So you should do whatever y=
ou think is best and kick BlackRock out of your office.

I think this approach is flawed, for at least two reasons:
=09You know a little bit about the preferences of BlackRock=E2=80=99s custo=
mers, don=E2=80=99t you? You know that they let BlackRock manage their mone=
y. That at least suggests that they might=C2=A0agree with the preferences t=
hat BlackRock=E2=80=99s managers express. It=E2=80=99s a weak signal, sure.=
 But it makes it hard to=C2=A0ignore=C2=A0BlackRock.=09BlackRock does get t=
o vote the stock, and if they vote you out of office you don=E2=80=99t get =
to say =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re a fake shareholder anyway!=E2=80=9D You have=
 to leave.

Here=E2=80=99s a fun  Wall Street Journal story about anti-ESG activist=C2=
=A0Vivek Ramaswamy of Strive Asset Management:

A conservative activist turned investor who has criticized Wall Street=E2=
=80=99s efforts to address climate change and other issues is publicly urgi=
ng Chevron Corp. to pump more fossil fuels over the next decade.
Vivek Ramaswamy, who launched an energy-focused exchange-traded fund nearly=
 a month ago, is among the most prominent critics of so-called environmenta=
l, social and governance=E2=80=94or ESG=E2=80=94investing. He quickly turne=
d his sights on Chevron, arguing the country=E2=80=99s second-biggest fossi=
l-fuel company should slow spending on its energy-transition plan, which he=
 said was partially motivated by pressure from top shareholders such as Bla=
ckRock Inc.=C2=A0
In the letter Tuesday to Chevron CEO Mike Wirth and the company=E2=80=99s b=
oard, Mr. Ramaswamy said he wanted to =E2=80=9Cliberate you from constraint=
s imposed on Chevron by its ESG-promoting =E2=80=98shareholders.=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

Notice his quotation marks around =E2=80=9Cshareholders.=E2=80=9D Here=E2=
=80=99s  the letter, which explains:

We understand that you are in a challenging position when Chevron=E2=80=99s=
 top =E2=80=9Cshareholders=E2=80=9D mandate your board to adopt a course of=
 action that you believe is not in the best interests of Chevron=E2=80=99s =
shareholders. But here is the reality: your purported =E2=80=9Cshareholders=
=E2=80=9D are not the actual owners of your company.
Today the three largest passive asset managers in the world =E2=80=93 Black=
Rock, State Street, and Vanguard =E2=80=93 manage over $20 trillion, approx=
imately equal to the total U.S. gross domestic product. In 2021 these firms=
 appeared in public filings as Chevron=E2=80=99s top 3 shareholders. By con=
trast, the actual owners of Chevron are not BlackRock, State Street, Vangua=
rd =E2=80=93 or, for that matter, Strive. Chevron=E2=80=99s actual owners a=
re the clients of these institutions: everyday citizens whose capital is in=
vested in passively managed index funds.
You owe a fiduciary duty to the actual owners of Chevron, not to the instit=
utions who claim to represent these owners. There is strong reason to belie=
ve that these large asset managers are not voting with their clients=E2=80=
=99 best interests in mind.

The context here is that 60% of Chevron=E2=80=99s shares  voted in favor of=
 reducing Chevron=E2=80=99s Scope 3 emissions in 2021, and Ramaswamy wants =
Chevron to ignore them. (As, legally, it totally can!) =E2=80=9COur goal in=
 writing this letter is to liberate you from constraints imposed on Chevron=
 by its ESG- promoting =E2=80=98shareholders,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D says the le=
tter, but it is a bit thin on=C2=A0how=C2=A0Strive will do its liberating. =
=E2=80=9CMr. Ramaswamy, whose fund holds a roughly 0.02% stake in Chevron, =
would likely need support from large shareholders who have generally embrac=
ed Chevron=E2=80=99s current strategy to get the company to change course,=
=E2=80=9D notes the Journal.
Chapter 1 of Jean Tirole=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C Theory of Corporate Finance=E2=
=80=9D says that =E2=80=9Cthe premise behind modern corporate finance in ge=
neral and this book in particular is that corporate insiders need not act i=
n the best interests of the providers of the funds=E2=80=9D: That is, the c=
entral issue in corporate finance is agency costs and conflicts of interest=
. Generally people think of this in terms of the conflict between the manag=
ers of a company and its shareholders. Sometimes they think of it in terms =
of the conflict between the managers of an investment fund and its clients.=
 But modern corporate finance is about all three: the managers of the compa=
ny, the professional managers of the investment funds that own its shares, =
and the clients of those investment funds. Typically the investment manager=
s tell the corporate managers that=C2=A0they=C2=A0represent the ultimate cl=
ients, but I guess there is nothing inevitable about that. Could the CEO of=
 Chevron tell BlackRock =E2=80=9Cno, you don=E2=80=99t own 6.99% of our sto=
ck, your clients do, and you don=E2=80=99t represent their interests, I do=
=E2=80=9D? Sure, I guess, why not.

