e the memorandum-of-understanding approach is  Tesla Inc.=E2=80=99s acquisi=
tion of SolarCity Corp., which we   discussed in April. I mean, not exactly=
, but Tesla did make a preliminary proposal of $28.50 per share in stock, e=
veryone sort of agreed to negotiate, they negotiated, diligence continued, =
and ultimately they agreed to a deal at a lower price because of what they =
found in due diligence. And because Elon Musk controlled both companies, th=
eir fairly casual decision to negotiate with each other felt *real* without=
 being *binding*: Musk was on both sides, so when he decided that Tesla sho=
uld buy SolarCity for $28.50-ish that meant that Tesla would probably buy S=
olarCity for $28.50-ish, but not certainly, and perhaps not for exactly tha=
t amount. Arguably that is the model that Musk has in mind for how public-c=
ompany mergers work: one where he controls both sides and can drop it at an=
y time.


  [3] In modern US public-company M&A practice this is often not considered=
 a valid excuse to get out of the deal =E2=80=94 there is often =E2=80=9Cno=
 financing out=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but, still, I am listing it as a thing th=
at can go wrong, because if the buyer really doesn=E2=80=99t have the money=
 at closing, that really is a problem.


  [4] I guess I will here? When Musk wanted to get out of the deal, the exc=
use he seized on was that he thinks that more than 5% of Twitter=E2=80=99s =
users are bots. This is a terrible excuse! For one thing, there=E2=80=99s n=
ever been any evidence at all that it=E2=80=99s true.   For another thing, =
Twitter never made any representation to him that fewer than 5% of its user=
s are bots.   For a third thing, when he was trying to buy Twitter, and whe=
n he signed the deal, Musk was going around crowing that Twitter had too ma=
ny bots and that he was going to clean them up, so the argument that he was=
 somehow tricked into believing there weren=E2=80=99t too many bots is insa=
ne. Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers realized that this was a terrible excuse, and   =
tried to cook up a better one for him. And, since the richest person in the=
 world is very publicly looking for some evidence that Twitter is a fraud, =
a disgruntled ex-employee publicized a whistle-blower complaint claiming th=
at Twitter is   doing lots of miscellaneous fraud, which Musk is now claimi=
ng to believe.=20


