10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oh Elon</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that the simplest explanation might be=
 that Elon Musk does not know what a merger agreement is. It is not uncommo=
n, in the world, for two companies to get together and discuss one buying t=
he other. And sometimes these talks will go well and they will get together=
 and=C2=A0sign some sort of document =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cmemorandum o=
f understanding,=E2=80=9D perhaps =E2=80=94=C2=A0that says, basically, =E2=
=80=9Cnow we are going to talk really seriously about me buying you.=E2=80=
=9D Sometimes they will have a price lined up=C2=A0when they sign this docu=
ment, say $54.20,=C2=A0and=C2=A0that price will be written into the documen=
t, and the expectation will be that eventually the buyer will pay $54.20 to=
 buy the seller. But things can go wrong. There will be continuing due dili=
gence, where the buyer examines the seller=E2=80=99s business, and the buye=
r might change its mind. Facts might come to light in due diligence that co=
uld make the buyer walk away or want to revise the price downward. The mark=
et might crash, making the seller less valuable or making it harder for the=
 buyer to get financing.=C2=A0The MOU is an agreement to talk more seriousl=
y; it reflects a general mutual desire to come to a deal at $54.20, but it =
is not binding. Nobody is committed to a deal at $54.20. Nothing is certain=
 until the final deal is signed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That, again, is a description of=C2=A0a thing =
that can happen in the world; some business acquisitions do go through a pr=
ocess=C2=A0like that. But it is not a description of<em> US public-company =
merger agreements</em>. In normal US public-company mergers, you don=E2=80=
=99t sign a memorandum saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re going to negotiate ser=
iously about buying you.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You=C2=A0negotiate seriously, and <em>then=C2=A0</em>you sign a m=
erger agreement saying =E2=80=9Cwe agree to buy you for $54.20.=E2=80=9D An=
d then if the buyer changes its mind, it still has to pay $54.20. And if th=
e market crashes, the buyer still has to pay $54.20. The deal is the deal; =
once it is signed, the merger agreement is binding and definitive.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is confusing, though. When you sign a publi=
c-company merger agreement, you do not immediately own the company you are =
buying. You are still months, perhaps years, away from the =E2=80=9Cclosing=
=E2=80=9D of the deal, when you actually pay the money and=C2=A0take over t=
he company. The delay is necessary to get regulatory approvals (antitrust, =
etc.), and to write a proxy statement and submit the merger to a vote of th=
e target=E2=80=99s shareholders. (You sign the merger agreement with the ta=
rget=E2=80=99s board of directors, but they don=E2=80=99t get the final say=
; the shareholders do.) Also, if you need to borrow money to buy the target=
, this delay gives you time to market the debt and actually get the money. =
(When you sign the deal, you probably=C2=A0have commitment letters from you=
r banks promising you the money, but by closing you can actually have the s=
pecific loans in place.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And during this delay, things can go wrong. Th=
e regulators might not approve. The shareholders might vote no. The financi=
ng might fall apart.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0When you sign the merger agreement, the buyer and seller agree to=
 work together and use their =E2=80=9Creasonable best efforts=E2=80=9D to g=
et the regulatory approvals and shareholder vote and financing and everythi=
ng else needed for the deal to close, but even if they do all of that somet=
imes it=E2=80=99s not enough, and the deal falls apart. Signing a merger ag=
reement doesn=E2=80=99t mean that the buyer will=C2=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0<=
/em>buy the seller. It is a serious binding commitment, but it is not 100%.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are the buyer, you might think about=C2=
=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>things that might go wrong. What if the seller=E2=80=
=99s business all burns to the ground in a fire? Seems unfair for you to ha=
ve to buy it anyway. What if the fire was the seller=E2=80=99s fault? What =
if it turns out that the seller was running a massive fraud and the whole b=
usiness is fake? Seems <em>really</em> unfair for you to have to buy it any=
way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so, yes, even if you get the regulatory an=
d shareholder approvals and the financing, there are still times when a buy=
er can get out of a deal between signing and closing. But they are quite li=
mited. The main one is that the seller makes representations in the merger =
agreement =E2=80=94=C2=A0statements about the company that it promises are =
true, things like =E2=80=9Cour financial statements are true=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cwe are not breaking any laws=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and if t=
hose statements are false, and they are=C2=A0<em>so=C2=A0</em>false that th=
ey would have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on the business, =
then the buyer can get out of the deal. (A typo in the financial statements=
 is not enough to get out of the deal, but inflating revenue for years migh=
t be.) That is a high bar, and=C2=A0Delaware courts =E2=80=94=C2=A0which he=
ar most big merger cases, since most public companies are incorporated in D=
elaware =E2=80=94 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
28977032.259543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjItMDUtMTMvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXRyb2xscy10d2l0dGVyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MDcyMl9NT05FWV=
NUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyM=
DkwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB60f55853" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  almost never find MAEs</a>. But in theory, yes, if the buyer was mi=
sled and the seller=E2=80=99s business is falling apart, the buyer can get =
out. And there are a very few other possible excuses; for instance, if the =
seller does not comply with its covenants =E2=80=94=C2=A0the things that it=
 agreed to do between signing and closing =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the buyer <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28977032.259543/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDYvZWxvbi1o=
YXMtYS1uZXctYm90LWV4Y3VzZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTA3MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA5MDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2da774cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  might have a=
n out</a>. Or if the buyer was tricked into signing the merger agreement by=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28977032.259543/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjkvbXVz=
ay10cmllcy1hLW5ldy13YXktb3V0LW9mLXR3aXR0ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkwNzIyX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOT=
A3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e397a07" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  intentional and material=C2=A0<em>fraud</em></a>, that would be an out=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the buyer can=E2=80=99t get out because it=
 changed its mind. Or because the market went down and it is overpaying. Or=
 because the market went down and it doesn=E2=80=99t have as much money as =
it used to. Or because the seller=E2=80=99s business turns out to be worse =
than the buyer thought in a general way. Broadly speaking, the merger agree=
ment is meant to be binding. Getting out of it is the exception.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk is trying to get out of the merger a=
greement he signed in April=C2=A0to buy Twitter Inc. for $54.20 per share, =
or about $44 billion total. He has good professional lawyers, and they are =
working hard, and certainly=C2=A0<em>they </em>know what a merger agreement=
 is, so all of Musk=E2=80=99s official statements and legal filings and so =
forth are phrased in terms of covenant violations and material adverse effe=
cts and fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it seems completely obvious to me that=C2=
=A0<em>Musk </em>doesn=E2=80=99t care about those magic words, and that he =
wants to get out of the deal for some combination of (1) the market went do=
wn and $54.20 per share=C2=A0looks pretty rich for Twitter, (2) the market =
went down and $44 billion looks like a big hit to Musk=E2=80=99s own wealth=
