<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Anti-ESG</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are the chief executive officer of a bi=
g integrated oil company, and holders of 60% of shares tell you that you sh=
ould focus more on renewable energy, should you do it? I actually think tha=
t this is a non-obvious question. Some considerations:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Possibly pivoting to renewables will c=
ost you more money now but increase long-term profits. Or perhaps not. You=
=E2=80=99re an oil-company CEO, though; I guess you=E2=80=99re the expert o=
n allocating capital to energy projects.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">You are a fiduciary for shareholders and you have your own ind=
ependent fiduciary obligation to do what is right for them. If you think th=
at focusing on renewables is the best long-term value-enhancing strategy fo=
r the company and its shareholders, you should do that. If you think that d=
rilling more oil is the best strategy, then you are in charge, and you shou=
ld do that. Your job is not to just do whatever they say; your job is to ma=
nage the company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That said, the s=
hareholders are not dummies =E2=80=94=C2=A0certainly=C2=A0lots=C2=A0of your=
 shares are held by institutional investors=C2=A0who are economically motiv=
ated and smart =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so if they think that renewables are a be=
tter strategy, you should at least hear them out. It is not=C2=A0<em>certai=
n=C2=A0</em>that you are a better allocator of capital to energy projects t=
han they are.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also, to the extent =
that=C2=A0your job is to do what is right for shareholders, their subjectiv=
e preferences might factor into it.=C2=A0Like if you think that focusing mo=
re on renewables will produce less income but=C2=A0<em>make your shareholde=
rs happy</em>, then, as a fiduciary for your shareholders, shouldn=E2=80=99=
t you do what makes them happy?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Al=
so, to the extent that your job is to=C2=A0<em>make the stock price go up=
=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0the simplest proxy for creating shareholder value=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, again, their subjective preferences might factor into=
 it. If you focus on renewables and that makes shareholders happy and they =
buy more stock and the stock goes up, then that is what matters, not the in=
come statement.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are a modern C=
EO and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28977032.25=
9543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgtMT=
kvbWF4aW1pemUtc2hhcmVob2xkZXItdmFsdWUtdG9wLWNlb3MtbWlnaHQtYmUtb3B0aW5nLW91d=
D9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTA3MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA5MDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBbdd7a481" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> you think about all stakeholders</a>, =
not just shareholder value. So even if your shareholders think you should p=
ivot to renewables and are correct that that is the right financial choice,=
 you might say =E2=80=9Cno I don=E2=80=99t want to lay off any oil drillers=
, so I=E2=80=99m sticking with drilling.=E2=80=9D (Or: You say =E2=80=9Csur=
e, shareholders, you are worried about financial returns, but I am worried =
about Europe=E2=80=99s resolve in resisting Russian aggression, so I am goi=
ng to drill to keep oil prices low.=E2=80=9D Lots of stakeholders!)</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is the fact that the shareholders o=
wn 60% of the stock and so they get to vote on stuff, so even if you don=E2=
=80=99t want to do what they want, you have to consider that your job is on=
 the line. Oh, maybe not, maybe not; it is very hard for even 60% of shareh=
olders to make=C2=A0<em>binding=C2=A0</em>changes at a big public company. =
But there is precedent: Exxon Mobil Corp. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/28977032.259543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZm=
lnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfbd28eac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  lost a proxy fight</a> with a tee=
ny tiny activist shareholder over issues like this. Big shareholders wanted=
 more renewables, Exxon wasn=E2=80=99t giving them what they wanted, so the=
 activist =E2=80=94=C2=A0a hedge fund called Engine No. 1 =E2=80=94=C2=A0ra=
n a proxy fight and got several Exxon directors replaced. If you ignore you=
r shareholders=E2=80=99 demands, they might get together and replace you to=
o.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All in all I think the basic answer is =E2=80=
=9Clisten respectfully to your shareholders, consider their arguments serio=
usly, be open to changing your mind, say soothing things to them, but ultim=
ately do what you think is best for the long-term value of the company even=
 if it=E2=80=99s not what shareholders say they want, and if you get fired=
=C2=A0then that=E2=80=99s life.=E2=80=9D But I could see arguments for othe=
r approaches.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is an approach that I honestly had not th=
ought of:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your shareholders are not your shareho=
lders. Most of your shares are held by big institutions like BlackRock Inc.=
, which manage money on behalf of thousands of individual customers. The st=
ated desires and subjective preferences of the managers at BlackRock Inc. a=
re irrelevant and you should ignore them. You cannot know the preferences o=
f BlackRock=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>customers</em>, because you do not deal with=
 them directly. So you should do whatever you think is best and kick BlackR=
ock out of your office.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think this approach is flawed, for at least =
two reasons:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You know a little bit about the prefe=
rences of BlackRock=E2=80=99s customers, don=E2=80=99t you? You know that t=
hey let BlackRock manage their money. That at least suggests that they <em>=
might=C2=A0</em>agree with the preferences that BlackRock=E2=80=99s manager=
s express. It=E2=80=99s a weak signal, sure. But it makes it hard to=C2=A0<=
em>ignore=C2=A0</em>BlackRock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bla=
ckRock does get to vote the stock, and if they vote you out of office you d=
on=E2=80=99t get to say =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re a fake shareholder anyway!=
=E2=80=9D You have to leave.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a fun <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28977032.259543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
hcnRpY2xlcy9hbnRpLWVzZy1hY3RpdmlzdC1pbnZlc3Rvci11cmdlcy1jaGV2cm9uLXRvLWluY3=
JlYXNlLW9pbC1wcm9kdWN0aW9uLTExNjYyNDk0NzY5P21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczM/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB8f0cbb02" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal story</a> about anti=
-ESG activist=C2=A0Vivek Ramaswamy of Strive Asset Management:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A conservative activist turned investor who ha=
s criticized Wall Street=E2=80=99s efforts to address climate change and ot=
her issues is publicly urging Chevron Corp. to pump more fossil fuels over =
the next decade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Vivek Ramaswamy, who launched an energy-focuse=
d exchange-traded fund nearly a month ago, is among the most prominent crit=
ics of so-called environmental, social and governance=E2=80=94or ESG=E2=80=
=94investing. He quickly turned his sights on Chevron, arguing the country=
=E2=80=99s second-biggest fossil-fuel company should slow spending on its e=
nergy-transition plan, which he said was partially motivated by pressure fr=
om top shareholders such as BlackRock Inc.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the letter Tuesday to Chevron CEO Mike Wirt=
h and the company=E2=80=99s board, Mr. Ramaswamy said he wanted to =E2=80=
=9Cliberate you from constraints imposed on Chevron by its ESG-promoting =
=E2=80=98shareholders.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice his quotation marks around =E2=80=9Csha=
reholders.=E2=80=9D Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/28977032.259543/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdHJpdmUuY29tL3N0cml2ZS1hc3NldC=
1tYW5hZ2VtZW50LWxldHRlci10by1jaGV2cm9uLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1778025d"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> the letter</a>, which explains:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We understand that you are in a challenging po=
sition when Chevron=E2=80=99s top =E2=80=9Cshareholders=E2=80=9D mandate yo=
ur board to adopt a course of action that you believe is not in the best in=
terests of Chevron=E2=80=99s shareholders. But here is the reality: your pu=
rported =E2=80=9Cshareholders=E2=80=9D are not the actual owners of your co=
mpany.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today the three largest passive asset managers=
 in the world =E2=80=93 BlackRock, State Street, and Vanguard =E2=80=93 man=
age over $20 trillion, approximately equal to the total U.S. gross domestic=
 product. In 2021 these firms appeared in public filings as Chevron=E2=80=
=99s top 3 shareholders. By contrast, the <em>actual</em> owners of Chevron=
 are not BlackRock, State Street, Vanguard =E2=80=93 or, for that matter, S=
trive. Chevron=E2=80=99s actual owners are the <em>clients</em> of these in=
stitutions: everyday citizens whose capital is invested in passively manage=
d index funds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You owe a fiduciary duty to the actual owners =
of Chevron, not to the institutions who claim to represent these owners. Th=
ere is strong reason to believe that these large asset managers are not vot=
ing with their clients=E2=80=99 best interests in mind.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The context here is that 60% of Chevron=E2=80=
=99s shares <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/289770=
32.259543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvO=
TM0MTAvMDAwMDA5MzQxMDIxMDAwMDIwL2N2eC0yMDIxMDUyNi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB9fcf3a4e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> voted in favor</a> of reducing Chevron=E2=80=99s Sc=
ope 3 emissions in 2021, and Ramaswamy wants Chevron to ignore them. (As, l=
egally, it totally can!) =E2=80=9COur goal in writing this letter is to lib=
erate you from constraints imposed on Chevron by its ESG- promoting =E2=80=
=98shareholders,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D says the letter, but it is a bit thin on=
=C2=A0<em>how=C2=A0</em>Strive will do its liberating. =E2=80=9CMr. Ramaswa=
my, whose fund holds a roughly 0.02% stake in Chevron, would likely need su=
pport from large shareholders who have generally embraced Chevron=E2=80=99s=
 current strategy to get the company to change course,=E2=80=9D notes the J=
ournal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chapter 1 of Jean Tirole=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28977032.259543/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9UaGVvcnktQ29ycG9yYXRlLUZpbmFuY2UtSmVhbi1UaXJvbGU=
vZHAvMDY5MTEyNTU2Mi9yZWY9c3JfMV8xP2tleXdvcmRzPXRpcm9sZStjb3Jwb3JhdGUrZmluYW=
5jZSZxaWQ9MTY2MjU3MDA5OCZzcj04LTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb49f97a5" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> Theory of Corporate Finance</a>=E2=80=9D says that =E2=80=9Cthe premise =
behind modern corporate finance in general and this book in particular is t=
hat corporate insiders need not act in the best interests of the providers =
of the funds=E2=80=9D: That is, the central issue in corporate finance is a=
gency costs and conflicts of interest. Generally people think of this in te=
rms of the conflict between the managers of a company and its shareholders.=
 Sometimes they think of it in terms of the conflict between the managers o=
f an investment fund and its clients. But modern corporate finance is about=
 all three: the managers of the company, the professional managers of the i=
nvestment funds that own its shares, and the clients of those investment fu=
nds. Typically the investment managers tell the corporate managers that=C2=
=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>represent the ultimate clients, but I guess there is =
nothing inevitable about that. Could the CEO of Chevron tell BlackRock =E2=
=80=9Cno, you don=E2=80=99t own 6.99% of our stock, your clients do, and yo=
u don=E2=80=99t represent their interests, I do=E2=80=9D? Sure, I guess, wh=
y not.</p>
